# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adolph-knopf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The **1918–1920 flu pandemic**, also known as the **Great Influenza epidemic** or by the misleading name **Spanish flu**, was an exceptionally deadly global influenza pandemic caused by the H1N1 subtype of the influenza A virus.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The earliest probable cases were documented in March 1918 in Haskell County, Kansas, United States, with further cases recorded in France, Germany and the United Kingdom in April.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Two years later, nearly a third of the global population, or an estimated 500 million people, had been infected.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Estimates of deaths range from 17 million to 50 million, and possibly as high as 100 million, making it one of the deadliest pandemics in history.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Limited historical epidemiological data make the pandemic's geographic origin indeterminate, with competing hypotheses on the initial spread.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Most influenza outbreaks disproportionately kill the young and old, but this pandemic had unusually high mortality for young adults.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Scientists offer several explanations for the high mortality, including a six-year climate anomaly affecting migration of disease vectors with increased likelihood of spread through bodies of water.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, the claim that young adults had a high mortality during the pandemic has been contested.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] World War I exacerbated malnourishment, overcrowding in medical camps and hospitals, and poor hygiene which in turn promoted bacterial superinfection, killing most of the victims after a typically prolonged death bed.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This pandemic was known by many different names depending on place, time, and context.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The etymology of alternative names historicises the scourge and its effects on people who would only learn years later that viruses caused influenza.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Outbreaks of influenza-like illness were documented in 1916–17 at British military hospitals in Étaples, France, and just across the English Channel at Aldershot, England.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Clinical indications in common with the 1918 pandemic included rapid symptom progression to a "dusky" heliotrope face.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This characteristic blue-violet cyanosis in expiring patients led to the name 'purple death'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In 1918, 'epidemic influenza', also known at the time as 'the grip' (French: *la grippe*, grasp), appeared in Kansas, U.S., during late spring, and early reports from Spain began appearing on 21 May.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Reports from both places called it 'three-day fever'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Many alternative names are exonyms in the practice of making new infectious diseases seem foreign.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This pattern was observed even before the 1889–1890 pandemic, also known as the 'Russian flu', when the Russians already called epidemic influenza the 'Chinese catarrh', the Germans called it the 'Russian pest', and the Italians called it the 'German disease'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] These epithets were re-used in the 1918 pandemic, along with new ones.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Outside Spain, the disease was soon misnamed 'Spanish influenza'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In a 2 June 1918 *The Times* of London dispatch titled, "The Spanish Epidemic," a correspondent in Madrid reported over 100,000 victims of, "The unknown disease...clearly of a gripal character," without referring to "Spanish influenza" directly.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Three weeks later *The Times* reported that, "Everybody thinks of it as the 'Spanish' influenza to-day." Three days after that an advertisement appeared in *The Times* for Formamint tablets to prevent "Spanish influenza".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] When it reached Moscow, *Pravda* announced, "*Ispánka* (the Spanish lady) is in town," making 'the Spanish lady' another common name.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The outbreak did not originate in Spain, but reporting did, due to wartime censorship in belligerent nations.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Spain was a neutral country unconcerned with appearances of combat readiness, and without a wartime propaganda machine to prop up morale, so its newspapers freely reported epidemic effects, making Spain the apparent locus of the epidemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The censorship was so effective that Spain's health officials were unaware its neighboring countries were similarly affected.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In an October 1918 "Madrid Letter" to the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, a Spanish official protested, "we were surprised to learn that the disease was making ravages in other countries, and that people there were calling it the 'Spanish grip'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] French press initially used 'American flu', but adopted 'Spanish flu' in lieu of antagonizing an ally.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the spring of 1918, British soldiers called it 'Flanders flu', while German soldiers used '*Flandern-Fieber*' (Flemish fever), both after a battlefield in Belgium where many soldiers on both sides fell ill.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Senegal it was named 'Brazilian flu', and in Brazil, 'German flu'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Spain it was also known as the 'French flu' (*gripe francesa*), or the 'Naples Soldier' (*Soldado de Nápoles*), after a popular song from a zarzuela.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Spanish flu (*gripe española*) is now a common name in Spain, but remains controversial there.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Othering derived from geopolitical borders and social boundaries.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Poland it was the 'Bolshevik disease', while in Russia it was referred to it as the 'Kirghiz disease'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Some Africans called it a 'white man's sickness', but in South Africa, white men also used the ethnophaulism *'kaffersiekte'* (lit.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Japan blamed sumo wrestlers for bringing the disease home from Taiwan, calling it 'sumo flu' (*Sumo Kaze*).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] World Health Organization 'best practices' first published in 2015 now aim to prevent social stigma by not associating culturally significant names with new diseases, listing "Spanish flu" under "examples to be avoided".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Many authors now eschew calling this the Spanish flu, instead using variations of '1918–19/20 flu/influenza pandemic'.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Some language endonyms did not name specific regions or groups of people.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This outbreak was also commonly known as the 'great influenza epidemic', after the 'great war', a common name for World War I before World War II.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] French military doctors originally called it 'disease 11' (*maladie onze*).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] German doctors downplayed the severity by calling it 'pseudo influenza' (Greek: *pseudo*, false), while in Africa, doctors tried to get patients to take it more seriously by calling it 'influenza vera' (Latin: *vera*, true).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A children's song from the 1889–90 flu pandemic was shortened and adapted into a skipping-rope rhyme popular in 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Despite its name, historical and epidemiological data cannot identify the geographic origin of the Spanish flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, several theories have been proposed.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The first confirmed cases originated in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Crosby stated in 2003 that the flu originated in Kansas, and author John M.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Barry described a January 1918 outbreak in Haskell County, Kansas, as the origin in his 2004 article.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A 2018 study of tissue slides and medical reports led by professor Michael Worobey found evidence against the disease originating from Kansas, as those cases were milder and had fewer deaths compared to the infections in New York City in the same period.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The study did find evidence through phylogenetic analyses that the virus likely had a North American origin, though it was not conclusive.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In addition, the haemagglutinin glycoproteins of the virus suggest that it originated long before 1918, and other studies suggest that the reassortment of the H1N1 virus likely occurred in or around 1915.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The major UK troop staging and hospital camp in Étaples in France has been theorized by virologist John Oxford as being at the center of the Spanish flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] His study found that in late 1916 the Étaples camp was hit by a new disease with high mortality that caused symptoms similar to the flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] According to Oxford, a similar outbreak occurred in March 1917 at army barracks in Aldershot, and military pathologists later recognized these early outbreaks as the same disease as the Spanish flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The overcrowded camp and hospital at Étaples was an ideal environment for the spread of a respiratory virus.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The hospital treated thousands of victims of poison gas attacks, and other casualties of war.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It also was home to a piggery, and poultry was regularly brought in to feed the camp.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Oxford and his team postulated that a precursor virus, harbored in birds, mutated and then migrated to pigs kept near the front.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A report published in 2016 in the *Journal of the Chinese Medical Association* found evidence that the 1918 virus had been circulating in the European armies for months and possibly years before the 1918 pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Political scientist Andrew Price-Smith published data from the Austrian archives suggesting the influenza began in Austria in early 1917.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Hannoun considered several alternative hypotheses of origin, such as Spain, Kansas, and Brest, as being possible, but not likely.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In 2014, historian Mark Humphries of the Memorial University of Newfoundland argued that the mobilization of 96,000 Chinese laborers to work behind the British and French lines might have been the source of the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Humphries found archival evidence that a respiratory illness that struck northern China (where the laborers came from) in November 1917 was identified a year later by Chinese health officials as identical to the Spanish flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] No tissue samples have survived for modern comparison.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Nevertheless, there were some reports of respiratory illness on the path the laborers took to get to Europe, which also passed through North America.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] China was one of the few regions of the world seemingly less affected by the Spanish flu pandemic, where several studies have documented a comparatively mild flu season in 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] (This is disputed due to lack of data during the Warlord Period.) This has led to speculation that the Spanish flu pandemic originated in China, as the lower mortality rates may be explained by the Chinese population's previously acquired immunity to the flu virus.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the Guangdong Province it was reported that early outbreaks of influenza in 1918 disproportionately impacted young men.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The June outbreak infected children and adolescents between 11 and 20 years of age, while the October outbreak was most common in those aged 11 to 15.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A report published in 2016 in the *Journal of the Chinese Medical Association* found no evidence that the 1918 virus was imported to Europe via Chinese and Southeast Asian soldiers and workers and instead found evidence of its circulation in Europe before the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Further evidence against the disease being spread by Chinese workers was that workers entered Europe through other routes that did not result in a detectable spread, making them unlikely to have been the original hosts.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The pandemic is conventionally marked as having begun on 4 March 1918 with the recording of the case of Albert Gitchell, an army cook at Camp Funston in Kansas despite there having been cases before him.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The disease had already been observed 200 miles (320 km) away in Haskell County as early as January 1918, prompting local doctor Loring Miner to warn the editors of the U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Public Health Service's journal *Public Health Reports*.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Within days of the 4 March case at Camp Funston, 522 men at the camp had reported sick.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By 11 March 1918, the virus had reached Queens, New York.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Failure to take preventive measures in March/April was later criticized.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] As the U.S. had entered World War I, the disease quickly spread from Camp Funston, a major training ground for troops of the American Expeditionary Forces, to other U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Army camps and Europe, becoming an epidemic in the Midwest, East Coast, and French ports by April 1918, and reaching the Western Front by mid-April.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It then quickly spread to the rest of France, Great Britain, Italy, and Spain and in May reached Wrocław and Odessa.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After the signing of the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk (March 1918), Germany started releasing Russian prisoners of war, who brought the disease to their country.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It reached North Africa, India, and Japan in May, and soon after had likely gone around the world as there had been recorded cases in Southeast Asia in April.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In June an outbreak was reported in China.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After reaching Australia in July, the wave started to recede.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The first wave lasted from the first quarter of 1918 and was relatively mild.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mortality rates were not appreciably above normal; in the United States ~75,000 flu-related deaths were reported in the first six months of 1918, compared to ~63,000 deaths during the same time period in 1915.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Madrid, Spain, fewer than 1,000 people died from influenza between May and June 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There were no reported quarantines; the first wave caused a significant disruption in the military operations of World War I, with three-quarters of French troops, half the British forces, and over 900,000 German soldiers sick.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second wave began in the second half of August 1918, probably spreading to Boston, Massachusetts and Freetown, Sierra Leone, by ships from Brest, where it had likely arrived with American troops or French recruits for naval training.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] From the Boston Navy Yard and Camp Devens, about 30 miles (48 km) west of Boston, other U.S. military sites were soon afflicted, as were troops being transported to Europe.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Helped by troop movements, it spread over the next two months to all of North America, and then to Central and South America, also reaching Brazil and the Caribbean on ships.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In July 1918, the Ottoman Empire saw its first cases, in soldiers.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] From Freetown, the pandemic spread through West Africa along the coast, rivers, and railways, and from railheads to more remote communities, while South Africa received it in September on ships bringing back members of the South African Native Labour Corps from France.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] From there it spread around southern Africa and beyond the Zambezi, reaching Ethiopia in November.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] On 15 September, New York City saw its first fatality from influenza.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The Philadelphia Liberty Loans Parade, held in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on 28 September 1918 to promote government bonds for World War I, resulted in an outbreak causing 12,000 deaths.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The celebrations of the Armistice of 11 November 1918 also caused outbreaks in Lima and Nairobi, but by December the wave was mostly over.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second wave of the 1918 pandemic was much more deadly than the first.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The first wave had resembled typical flu epidemics; those most at risk were the sick and elderly, while younger, healthier people recovered easily.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] October 1918 was the month with the highest fatality rate of the whole pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the United States, ~292,000 deaths were reported between September–December 1918, compared to ~26,000 during the same time period in 1915.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The Netherlands reported over 40,000 deaths from influenza and acute respiratory disease.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Bombay reported ~15,000 deaths in a population of 1.1 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The 1918 flu pandemic in India was especially deadly, as Historian David Arnold estimates at least 12 million dead, about 5% of the population.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Pandemic activity persisted into 1919 in many places, possibly attributable to climate, specifically in the Northern Hemisphere, where it was winter and thus the usual time for influenza activity.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The pandemic nonetheless continued into 1919 largely independent of region and climate.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Cases began to rise again in some parts of the U.S. as early as late November 1918, with the Public Health Service issuing its first report of a "recrudescence of the disease" in "widely scattered localities" in early December.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This resurgent activity varied across the country, however, possibly on account of differing restrictions.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Michigan, for example, experienced a swift resurgence of influenza that reached its peak in December, possibly as a result of the lifting of the ban on public gatherings.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Pandemic interventions, such as bans on public gatherings and the closing of schools, were reimposed in many places in an attempt to suppress the spread.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There was "a very sudden and very marked rise in general death rate" in most cities in January 1919; nearly all experienced "some degree of recrudescence" of the flu in January and February.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Significant outbreaks occurred in cities including Los Angeles, New York City, Memphis, Nashville, San Francisco, and St.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By 21 February, with some local variation, influenza activity was reported to have been declining since mid-January in all parts of the country.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Following this "first great epidemic period" that had commenced in October 1918, deaths from pneumonia and influenza were "somewhat below average" in large U.S. cities between May 1919 and January 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Nonetheless, nearly 160,000 deaths were attributed to these causes in the first six months of 1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It was not until later in the winter and into the spring that a clearer resurgence appeared in Europe.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A significant third wave had developed in England and Wales by mid-February, peaking in early March, though it did not fully subside until May.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] France also experienced a significant wave that peaked in February, alongside the Netherlands.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Norway, Finland, and Switzerland saw recrudescences of pandemic activity in March, and Sweden in April.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Much of Spain was affected by "a substantial recrudescent wave" of influenza between January and April 1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Portugal experienced a resurgence in pandemic activity that lasted from March to September 1919, with the greatest impact being felt on the west coast and in the north of the country; all districts were affected between April and May specifically.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Influenza entered Australia for the first time in January 1919 after a strict maritime quarantine had shielded the country through 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It assumed epidemic proportions first in Melbourne, peaking in mid-February.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The flu soon appeared in neighboring New South Wales and South Australia.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] New South Wales experienced its first wave of infection between mid-March and late May, while a second, more severe wave occurred in Victoria between April and June.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Land quarantine measures hindered the spread of the disease.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Queensland was not infected until late April; Western Australia avoided the disease until early June, and Tasmania remained free from it until mid-August.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Out of the six states, Victoria and New South Wales experienced generally more extensive epidemics.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Each experienced another significant wave of illness over the winter.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second epidemic in New South Wales was more severe than the first, while Victoria saw a third wave that was somewhat less extensive than its second, more akin to its first.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The disease also reached other parts of the world for the first time in 1919, such as Madagascar, which saw its first cases in April; the outbreak had spread to practically all sections of the island by June.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In other parts, influenza recurred in the form of a true "third wave".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Hong Kong experienced another outbreak in June, as did South Africa during its fall and winter months in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] New Zealand experienced some cases in May.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Parts of South America experienced a resurgence of pandemic activity throughout 1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A third wave hit Brazil between January and June.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Between July 1919 and February 1920, Chile, which had been affected for the first time in October 1918, experienced a severe second wave, with mortality peaking in August 1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Montevideo similarly experienced a second outbreak between July and September.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The third wave particularly affected Spain, Serbia, Mexico and Great Britain, resulting in hundreds of thousands of deaths.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the Northern Hemisphere, fears of a "recurrence" of the flu grew as fall approached.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Experts cited past flu epidemics, such as that of 1889–1890, to predict that such a recurrence a year later was not unlikely, though not all agreed.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Surgeon General Rupert Blue said a return of the flu later in the year would "probably, but by no means certainly," occur.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] France had readied a public information campaign before the end of the summer, and Britain began preparations in the autumn with the manufacture of vaccine.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Japan, the flu broke out again in December and spread rapidly throughout the country, a fact attributed at the time to cold weather.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Pandemic-related measures were renewed to check the outbreak, and health authorities recommended the use of masks.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The epidemic intensified in the latter part of December before swiftly peaking in January.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Between October 1919 and 23 January 1920, 780,000 cases were reported across the country, with at least 20,000 deaths recorded by that date.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This apparently reflected "a condition of severity three times greater than for the corresponding period of" 1918–1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Nonetheless, the disease was regarded as being milder than it had been the year before, albeit more infectious.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Despite its rapid peak at the beginning of the year, the outbreak persisted throughout the winter, before subsiding in the spring.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the United States, there were "almost continuously isolated or solitary cases" of flu throughout the spring and summer of 1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] An increase in scattered cases became apparent as early as September, but Chicago experienced one of the first major outbreaks of the flu beginning in the middle of January.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The Public Health Service announced it would take steps to "localize the epidemic", but the disease was already causing a simultaneous outbreak in Kansas City and quickly spread outward from the center of the country.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A few days after its first announcement, PHS issued another assuring that the disease was under the control of state health authorities and that an outbreak of epidemic proportions was not expected.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] It became apparent within days of the start of Chicago's explosive growth in cases that the flu was spreading in the city at an even faster rate than in winter 1919, though fewer were dying.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Within a week, new cases in the city had surpassed its peak during the 1919 wave.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Around the same time, New York City began to see its own sudden increase in cases, and other cities around the country were soon to follow.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Certain pandemic restrictions, such as the closing of schools and theaters and the staggering of business hours to avoid congestion, were reimposed in cities like Chicago, Memphis, and New York City.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] As they had during the epidemic in fall 1918, schools in New York City remained open, while those in Memphis were shuttered as part of restrictions on public gatherings.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The fourth wave in the United States subsided as swiftly as it had appeared, reaching a peak in early February.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] "An epidemic of considerable proportions marked the early months of 1920", the U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mortality Statistics would later note; according to data at this time, the epidemic resulted in one third as many deaths as the 1918–1919 experience.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] New York City alone reported 6,374 deaths between December 1919 and April 1920, almost twice the number of the first wave in spring 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Detroit, Milwaukee, Kansas City, Minneapolis, and St.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Louis were hit particularly hard, with death rates higher than all of 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Hawaii experienced its peak of the pandemic in early 1920, recording 1,489 deaths from flu-related causes, compared with 615 in 1918 and 796 in 1919.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By contrast, the outbreak in western Europe was considered "benign", with the age distribution of deaths beginning to take on that of seasonal flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Spain, Denmark, Finland, Germany and Switzerland recorded a late peak between January–April 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mexico experienced a fourth wave between February and March.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In South America, Peru experienced "asynchronous recrudescent waves" throughout the year.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A severe third wave hit Lima, the capital city, between January and March, resulting in an all-cause excess mortality rate approximately four times greater than that of the 1918–1919 wave.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Ica similarly experienced another severe pandemic wave in 1920, between July and October.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A fourth wave also occurred in Brazil, in February.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Korea and Taiwan experienced pronounced outbreaks in late 1919 and early 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] By mid-1920, the pandemic was largely considered to be "over" by the public as well as governments.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Though parts of Chile experienced a third, milder wave between November 1920 and March 1921, the flu seemed to be mostly absent through the winter of 1920–1921.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the United States, for example, deaths from pneumonia and influenza were "very much lower than for many years".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Seasonal influenza began to be reported again from many places in 1921.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Influenza continued to be felt in Chile, where a post-pandemic fourth wave affected 7 of its 24 provinces between June and December 1921.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The winter of 1921–1922 was the first major reappearance of seasonal influenza in the Northern Hemisphere, in many parts its most significant occurrence since the main pandemic in late 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Northwestern Europe was particularly affected.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] All-cause mortality in the Netherlands approximately doubled in January 1922 alone.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Helsinki, a major epidemic (the fifth since 1918) prevailed between November and December 1921.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The flu was also widespread in the United States, its prevalence in California reportedly greater in early March 1922 than at any point since the pandemic ended in 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the years after 1920, the disease came to represent the "seasonal flu".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The virus, H1N1, remained endemic, occasionally causing more severe or otherwise notable outbreaks.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The period since its initial appearance in 1918 has been termed a "pandemic era", in which all flu pandemics have been caused by its own descendants.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Following the first of these post-1918 pandemics, in 1957, the virus was totally displaced by the novel H2N2, the reassortant product of the human H1N1 and an avian influenza virus, which thereafter became the active influenza A virus in humans.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In 1977, an influenza virus bearing a very close resemblance to the seasonal H1N1, which had not been seen since the 1950s, appeared in the USSR and subsequently initiated a "technical" pandemic that principally affected those 26 and under.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Following this miniature pandemic, the reemerged H1N1 became endemic again but did not displace the other active influenza A virus, H3N2 (which itself had displaced H2N2 through a pandemic in 1968).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] For the first time, two influenza A viruses were observed in cocirculation.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This state has persisted even after 2009, when a novel H1N1 virus emerged, sparked a pandemic, and thereafter took the place of the seasonal H1N1 to circulate alongside H3N2.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The basic reproduction number of the virus was between 2 and 3.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The close quarters and massive troop movements of World War I hastened the pandemic, and probably both increased transmission and augmented mutation.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The war may also have reduced people's resistance to the virus.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Some speculate the soldiers' immune systems were weakened by malnourishment and the stresses of combat and chemical attacks, increasing their susceptibility.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Modern transportation systems and increased travel was a significant factor in the worldwide occurrence.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Another was lies and denial by governments, leaving the population ill-prepared to handle the outbreaks.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The severity of the second wave has been attributed to the First World War.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In civilian life, natural selection favors a mild strain.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Those who get very ill stay home, and those mildly ill continue with their lives, preferentially spreading the mild strain.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In the trenches, natural selection was reversed.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Soldiers with a mild strain stayed where they were, while the severely ill were sent on crowded trains to crowded field hospitals, spreading the deadlier virus.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The second wave began, and the flu quickly spread around the world again.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] (During modern pandemics, health officials look for deadlier strains of a virus when it reaches places with social upheaval.) The fact that most of those who recovered from first-wave infections had become immune showed that it must have been the same strain of flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This was most dramatically illustrated in Copenhagen, which escaped with a combined mortality rate of 0.29% (0.02% in the first wave and 0.27% in the second wave) because of exposure to the less-lethal first wave.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After the lethal second wave, new cases dropped abruptly.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Philadelphia, for example, 4,597 people died in the week ending 16 October, but by 11 November, influenza had almost disappeared from the city.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] One explanation for the rapid decline in lethality is that doctors became more effective in the prevention and treatment of pneumonia that developed after the victims had contracted the virus.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, John Barry stated in his 2004 book *The Great Influenza: The Epic Story of the Deadliest Plague In History* that researchers have found no evidence to support this position.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Another theory holds that the 1918 virus mutated extremely rapidly to a less lethal strain.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Such evolution of influenza is a common occurrence: there is a tendency for pathogenic viruses to become less lethal with time, as the hosts of more dangerous strains tend to die out.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Fatal cases did continue into 1919, however.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] One notable example was that of ice hockey player Joe Hall, who died of the flu in April after an outbreak that resulted in the cancellation of the 1919 Stanley Cup Final.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The majority of the infected experienced only the typical flu symptoms of sore throat, headache, and fever, especially during the first wave.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] However, during the second wave, the disease was much more serious, often complicated by bacterial pneumonia, which was often the cause of death.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This more serious type would cause *heliotrope cyanosis* to develop, whereby the skin would first develop two mahogany spots over the cheekbones which would then over a few hours color the entire face blue, followed by black coloration first in the extremities and then the limbs and the torso.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Death would follow within hours or days due to the lungs being filled with fluids.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Other signs and symptoms reported included spontaneous mouth and nosebleeds, miscarriages for pregnant women, a peculiar smell, teeth and hair falling out, delirium, dizziness, insomnia, loss of hearing or smell, and impaired vision.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] One observer wrote, "One of the most striking of the complications was hemorrhage from mucous membranes, especially from the nose, stomach, and intestine.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Bleeding from the ears and petechial hemorrhages in the skin also occurred".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The majority of deaths were from bacterial pneumonia, a common secondary infection associated with influenza.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This pneumonia was itself caused by common upper respiratory-tract bacteria, which were able to get into the lungs via the damaged bronchial tubes.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The virus also killed people directly by causing massive hemorrhages and edema in the lungs.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Modern analysis has shown the virus to be particularly deadly because in animal trials it triggers an overreaction of the body's immune system (cytokine storm).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The strong immune reactions of young adults were postulated to have ravaged the body, whereas the weaker immune reactions of children and middle-aged adults resulted in fewer deaths.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Because the virus that caused the disease was too small to be seen under a microscope at the time, there were problems with correctly diagnosing it.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The bacterium *Haemophilus influenzae* was instead mistakenly thought to be the cause, as it was big enough to be seen and was present in many, though not all, patients.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] For this reason, a vaccine that was used against that bacillus did not make infection rarer but did decrease the death rate.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] During the deadly second wave there were also fears that it was in fact plague, dengue fever, or cholera.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Another misdiagnosis was typhus, which was common in circumstances of social upheaval, and was therefore also affecting Russia in the aftermath of the October Revolution.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Chile, the view of the country's elite was that the nation was in severe decline, and therefore doctors assumed that the disease was typhus caused by poor hygiene, causing a mismanaged response which did not ban mass gatherings.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Studies have shown that the immune system of Spanish flu victims could have been weakened by unseasonably cold and wet weather for extended periods during the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] This affected especially troops exposed to incessant rains and lower-than-average temperatures during World War I, and especially during the second wave of the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Specifically, a significant increase in precipitation affected all of Europe during the second wave of the pandemic, from September to December 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Mortality figures follow closely the concurrent increase in precipitation and decrease in temperatures.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The climate anomaly likely influenced the migration of H1N1 avian vectors which contaminate bodies of water with their droppings, reaching 60% infection rates in autumn.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The climate anomaly has been associated with an anthropogenic increase in atmospheric dust, due to the incessant bombardment; increased nucleation due to dust particles (cloud condensation nuclei) contributed to increased precipitation.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In September 1918, the Red Cross recommended two-layer gauze masks to halt the spread of "plague".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] , limitations on crowd size, selective closing of businesses, curfews, and lockdowns.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] After October's strict containment measures showed some success, Armistice Day celebrations in November and relaxed attitudes by Thanksgiving caused a resurgence.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] While systems for alerting public health authorities of infectious spread did exist in 1918, they did not generally include influenza, leading to a delayed response.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Maritime quarantines were declared on islands such as Iceland, Australia, and American Samoa, saving many lives.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Social distancing measures were introduced, for example closing schools, theatres, and places of worship, limiting public transportation, and banning mass gatherings.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Wearing face masks became common in some places, such as Japan, though there were debates over their efficacy.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There was also some resistance to their use, as exemplified by the Anti-Mask League of San Francisco.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Vaccines were developed, but as these were based on bacteria and not the actual virus, they could only help with secondary infections.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] To a large extent, the New York City health commissioner ordered businesses to open and close on staggered shifts to avoid overcrowding on the subways.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] A later study found that measures such as banning mass gatherings and requiring the wearing of face masks could cut the death rate up to 50 percent, but this was dependent on their being imposed early in the outbreak and not being lifted prematurely.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] As there were no antiviral drugs to treat the virus, and no antibiotics to treat the secondary bacterial infections, doctors would rely on an assortment of medicines with varying degrees of effectiveness, such as aspirin, quinine, arsenics, digitalis, strychnine, epsom salts, castor oil, and iodine.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Traditional treatments, such as bloodletting, ayurveda, and kampo, were also applied.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Due to World War I, many countries engaged in wartime censorship, and suppressed reporting of the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] For example, the Italian newspaper *Corriere della Sera* was prohibited from reporting daily death tolls.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] The newspapers of the time were also generally paternalistic and worried about mass panic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] Misinformation also spread along with the disease.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] In Ireland there was a belief that noxious gases were rising from the mass graves of Flanders Fields and being "blown all over the world by winds".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p01] There were also rumors that the Germans were behind it, for example by poisoning the aspirin manufactured by Bayer, or by releasing poison gas from U-boats.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The Spanish flu infected around 500 million people, about one-third of the world's population.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Estimates on deaths vary greatly, but it is considered to be one of the deadliest pandemics in history.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] An early estimate from 1927 put global mortality at 21.6 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] An estimate from 1991 states that the virus killed between 25 and 39 million people.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2005 estimate put the death toll at 50 million, and possibly as high as 100 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, a 2018 reassessment in the *American Journal of Epidemiology* estimated the total to be about 17 million, though this has been contested.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Barry have the total death toll alone at well above 100 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] With a world population of 1.8 to 1.9 billion, these estimates correspond to between 1 and 6 percent of the population.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2009 study in *Influenza and Other Respiratory Viruses* based on data from fourteen European countries estimated a total of 2.64 million excess deaths in Europe attributable to the Spanish flu during the 1918–1919 phase of the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This represents a mortality rate of about 1.1% of the European population (c.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] 250 million in 1918), considerably higher than the mortality rate in the U.S., which the authors hypothesize is likely due to the severe effects of the war in Europe.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The excess mortality rate in the U.K. has been estimated at 0.28%–0.4%, far below this European average.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some 12–17 million people died in India, about 5% of the population.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The death toll in India's British-ruled districts was 13.88 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another estimate gives at least 12 million dead.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The decade between 1911 and 1921 was the only census period in which India's population fell, mostly due to devastation of the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Japan, the flu killed nearly 500,000 people over two waves between 1918 and 1920, with nearly 300,000 excess deaths between October 1918 and May 1919 and 182,000 between December 1919 and May 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the Dutch East Indies (now Indonesia), 1.5 million were assumed to have died among 30 million inhabitants.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Tahiti, 13% of the population died in one month.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarly, in Western Samoa 22% of the population of 38,000 died within two months.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Istanbul, capital of the Ottoman Empire, 6,403 to 10,000 died, giving the city a mortality rate of at least 0.56%.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In New Zealand, the flu killed an estimated 6,400 *Pākehā* (or "New Zealanders primarily of European descent") and 2,500 Māori in six weeks, with Māori dying at eight times the rate of *Pākehā*.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Australia, the flu killed around 12,000 to 20,000 people.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The country's death rate, 2.7 per 1,000 people, was one of the lowest recorded; however, as much as 40 percent of the population were infected, and a mortality rate of 50 percent was recorded by some Aboriginal communities.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] New South Wales and Victoria saw the greatest relative mortality, with 3.19 and 2.40 deaths per 1,000 people respectively, while Western Australia, Queensland, Southern Australia, and Tasmania experienced rates of 1.70, 1.14, 1.13, and 1.09 per 1,000 respectively.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Queensland, at least one-third of deaths recorded were in the Aboriginal population.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the U.S., about 20 million out of a population of 105 million became infected in the 1918–1919 season, and an estimated 500,000 to 850,000 died (0.5 to 0.8 percent of the U.S. population).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Native Americans tribes were particularly affected.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the Four Corners area, there were 3,293 registered deaths among Native Americans.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Entire Inuit and Alaskan Native village communities died in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Brazil, 300,000 died, including president Rodrigues Alves.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the UK, as many as 250,000 died; in France, more than 400,000.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Ghana, the influenza epidemic killed at least 100,000 people.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Tafari Makonnen (the future Emperor of Ethiopia) was one of the first Ethiopians who contracted influenza but survived.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Estimates for fatalities in the capital city, Addis Ababa, range from 5,000 to 10,000, or higher.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The death toll in Russia has been estimated at 450,000, though the epidemiologists who suggested this number called it a "shot in the dark".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] If it is correct, Russia lost roughly 0.4% of its population, meaning it suffered the lowest influenza-related mortality in Europe.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another study considers this number unlikely, given that the country was in the grip of a civil war, and the infrastructure of daily life had broken down; the study suggests that Russia's death toll was closer to 2%, or 2.7 million people.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Even in areas where mortality was low, so many adults were incapacitated that daily life was hampered.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some communities closed all stores or required customers to leave orders outside.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There were reports that healthcare workers could not tend the sick nor the gravediggers bury the dead because they too were ill.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Mass graves were dug by steam shovel and bodies buried without coffins in many places.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Bristol Bay, a region of Alaska populated by Indigenous people, suffered a death rate of 40 percent, with some villages entirely disappearing.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Nenana, Alaska, avoided the extent of the pandemic between 1918 and 1919, but the flu at last reached the town in spring 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Reports suggested that during the first two weeks of May, the majority of the town's population became infected; 10% of the population were estimated to have died, most of whom were Alaska Natives.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Several Pacific island territories were hit particularly hard.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The pandemic reached them from New Zealand, which was too slow to implement measures to prevent ships carrying the flu from leaving its ports.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] From New Zealand, the flu reached Tonga (killing 8% of the population), Nauru (16%), and Fiji (5%, 9,000 people).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Worst affected was Western Samoa, which had been occupied by New Zealand in 1914.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] 90% of the population was infected; 30% of adult men, 22% of adult women, and 10% of children died.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The disease spread fastest through the higher social classes among the Indigenous peoples, because of the custom of gathering oral tradition from chiefs on their deathbeds; many community elders were infected through this process.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Iran, the mortality was estimated at between 902,400 and 2,431,000, or 8% to 22% of the total population.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The country was going through the Persian famine of 1917–1919 concurrently.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Ireland, during the worst 12 months, the Spanish flu accounted for one-third of all deaths.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In South Africa it is estimated that about 300,000 people amounting to 6% of the population died within six weeks.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Government actions in the early stages of the virus' arrival in the country in September 1918 are believed to have unintentionally accelerated its spread.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Almost a quarter of the working population of Kimberley, consisting of workers in the diamond mines, died.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In British Somaliland, one official estimated that 7% of the native population died.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This huge death toll resulted from an extremely high infection rate of up to 50% and the extreme severity of the symptoms.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the Pacific, American Samoa and the French colony of New Caledonia succeeded in preventing even a single death from influenza through effective quarantines.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, the outbreak was delayed into 1926 for American Samoa and 1921 for New Caledonia as the quarantine period ended.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] On American Samoa, at least 25% of the island residents were clinically attacked and 0.1% died, and on New Caledonia, there was widespread illness and 0.1% population died.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Australia also managed to avoid the first two waves with a quarantine.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Iceland protected a third of its population from exposure by blocking the main road of the island.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] By the end of the pandemic, the isolated island of Marajó, in Brazil's Amazon River Delta had not reported an outbreak.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Estimates for the death toll in China have varied widely, reflecting the lack of centralized collection of health data at the time due to the Warlord period.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] China may have experienced a relatively mild flu season in 1918 compared to other areas of the world.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, some reports from its interior suggest that mortality rates from influenza were perhaps higher in at least a few locations in 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] At the very least, there is little evidence that China as a whole was seriously affected by the flu compared to other countries.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The first estimate of the Chinese death toll was made in 1991 by Patterson and Pyle, which estimated a toll of between 5 and 9 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, this study was criticized by later studies due to flawed methodology, and newer studies have published estimates of a far lower mortality rate in China.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] For instance, Iijima in 1998 estimates the death toll in China to be between 1 and 1.28 million based on data available from Chinese port cities.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The lower estimates of the Chinese death toll are based on the low mortality rates that were found in Chinese port cities and on the assumption that poor communications prevented the flu from penetrating the interior of China.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, some contemporary newspaper and post office reports, as well as reports from missionary doctors, suggest that the flu did penetrate the Chinese interior and that influenza was severe in at least some locations in the countryside of China.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Although medical records from China's interior are lacking, extensive medical data were recorded in Chinese port cities, such as then British-controlled Hong Kong, Canton, Peking, Harbin and Shanghai.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These data were collected by the Chinese Maritime Customs Service, which was largely staffed by non-Chinese foreigners.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] As a whole, data from China's port cities show low mortality rates compared to other cities in Asia.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] For example, the British authorities at Hong Kong and Canton reported a mortality rate from influenza at a rate of 0.25% and 0.32%, much lower than the reported mortality rate of other cities in Asia, such as Calcutta or Bombay, where influenza was much more devastating.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarly, in the city of Shanghai – which had a population of over 2 million – there were only 266 recorded deaths from influenza among the Chinese population in 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] If extrapolated from the extensive data recorded from Chinese cities, the suggested mortality rate from influenza in China as a whole in 1918 was likely lower than 1% – much lower than the world average (which was around 3–5%).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In contrast, Japan and Taiwan had reported a mortality rate from influenza around 0.45% and 0.69% respectively, higher than the mortality rate collected from data in Chinese port cities, such as Hong Kong (0.25%), Canton (0.32%), and Shanghai.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, the influenza mortality rate in Hong Kong and Canton are under-recorded, because only the deaths that occurred in colony hospitals were counted.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarly, in Shanghai, these statistics are limited to that area of the city under the control of the health section of the Shanghai International Settlement; the actual death toll in Shanghai was much higher.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The medical records from China's interior indicate that, compared to cities, rural communities have substantially higher mortality rate.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A published influenza survey in Houlu County, Hebei Province, found that the case fatality rate was 9.77% and 0.79% of county population died from influenza in October and November 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The pandemic mostly killed young adults.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 1918–1919, 99% of pandemic influenza deaths in the U.S. occurred in people under 65, and nearly half of deaths were in young adults 20 to 40 years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 1920, the mortality rate among people under 65 had decreased sixfold to half the mortality rate of people over 65, but 92% of deaths still occurred in people under 65.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This is unusual since influenza is typically most deadly to weak individuals, such as infants under age two, adults over age 70, and the immunocompromised.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 1918, older adults may have had partial protection caused by exposure to the 1889–1890 flu pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Barry, the most vulnerable of all were pregnant women.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] He reported that in thirteen studies of hospitalized women in the pandemic, the death rate ranged from 23% to 71%.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Of the pregnant women who survived childbirth, over one-quarter (26%) lost the child.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another oddity was that the outbreak was widespread in the summer and autumn (in the Northern Hemisphere); influenza is usually worse in winter.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There were also geographic patterns to the disease's fatality.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some parts of Asia had 30 times higher death rates than some parts of Europe, and generally, Africa and Asia had higher rates, while Europe and North America had lower ones.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There was also great variation within continents, with three times higher mortality in Hungary and Spain compared to Denmark, two to three times higher chance of death in Sub-Saharan Africa compared to North Africa, and possibly up to ten times higher rates between the extremes of Asia.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Cities were affected worse than rural areas.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There were also differences between cities, which might have reflected exposure to the milder first wave giving immunity, as well as the introduction of social distancing measures.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Another major pattern was the differences between social classes.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In Oslo, death rates were inversely correlated with apartment size, as the poorer people living in smaller apartments died at a higher rate.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Social status was also reflected in the higher mortality among immigrant communities, with Italian Americans, a recently arrived group at the time, nearly twice as likely to die compared to the average Americans.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These disparities reflected worse diets, crowded living conditions, and problems accessing healthcare.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Paradoxically, however, African Americans were relatively spared.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] More men than women were killed by the flu, as they were more likely to go out and be exposed, while women tended to stay at home.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] For the same reason men also were more likely to have pre-existing tuberculosis, which severely worsened the chances of recovery.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, in India the opposite was true, potentially because Indian women were neglected with poorer nutrition, and were expected to care for the sick.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] (2011) examined the factors that underlie variability in temporal patterns and their correlation to patterns of mortality and morbidity.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Their analysis suggests that temporal variations in transmission rate provide the best explanation, and the variation in transmission required to generate these three waves is within biologically plausible values.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] (2013) used a simple epidemic model incorporating three factors to infer the cause of the three waves of the 1918 influenza pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These factors were school opening and closing, temperature changes throughout the outbreak, and human behavioral changes in response to the outbreak.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Their modeling results showed that all three factors are important, but human behavioral responses showed the most significant effects.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Academic Andrew Price-Smith has argued that the virus helped tip the balance of power in the latter days of the war towards the Allied cause.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] He provides data that the viral waves hit the Central Powers before the Allied powers and that morbidity and mortality in Germany and Austria were considerably higher than in Britain and France.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2006 *Lancet* study corroborates higher excess mortality rates in Germany (0.76%) and Austria (1.61%) compared to Britain (0.34%) and France (0.75%).
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Kenneth Kahn at Oxford University Computing Services writes that "Many researchers have suggested that the conditions of the war significantly aided the spread of the disease.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] And others have argued that the course of the war (and subsequent peace treaty) was influenced by the pandemic." Kahn has developed a model that can be used to test these theories.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Many businesses in the entertainment and service industries suffered losses in revenue, while the healthcare industry reported profit gains.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Historian Nancy Bristow has argued that the pandemic, when combined with the increasing number of women attending college, contributed to the success of women in nursing.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This was due in part to the failure of medical doctors, who were predominantly men, to contain the illness.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Nursing staff, who were mainly women, celebrated the success of their patient care and did not associate the spread of the disease with their work.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] A 2020 study found that U.S. cities that implemented early and extensive non-medical measures (quarantine, etc.) suffered no additional adverse economic effects due to implementing those measures.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, the validity of this study has been questioned because of the coincidence of WWI and other problems with data reliability.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The flu has also been linked to the outbreak of encephalitis lethargica in the 1920s.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Survivors faced an elevated mortality risk.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Some survivors did not fully recover from physiological conditions resulting from infection.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The Spanish flu began to fade from public awareness over the decades until the bird flu and other pandemics in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This has led some historians to label the Spanish flu a "forgotten pandemic".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] However, this label has been challenged by the historian Guy Beiner, who demonstrated how the pandemic was overshadowed by the commemoration of the First World War and mostly neglected in mainstream historiography, yet was remembered in private and local traditions across the globe.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] There are various theories of why the Spanish flu was "forgotten".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The rapid pace of the pandemic, which killed most of its victims in the United States within less than nine months, resulted in limited media coverage.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The general population was familiar with patterns of pandemic disease in the late 19th and early 20th centuries: typhoid, yellow fever, diphtheria, and cholera all occurred near the same time.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These outbreaks probably lessened the significance of the influenza pandemic for the public.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In some areas, the flu was not reported on, the only mention being that of advertisements for medicines claiming to cure it.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Additionally, the outbreak coincided with the deaths and media focus on the First World War.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The majority of fatalities, from both the war and the epidemic, were among young adults.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The high number of war-related deaths of young adults may have overshadowed the deaths caused by flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Particularly in Europe, where the war's toll was high, the flu may not have had a tremendous psychological impact or may have seemed an extension of the war's tragedies.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The last known person to have survived the Spanish flu, José Ameal Peña, was alive as of 2020.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Despite the toll of the pandemic, it was never a large theme in American literature.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Alfred Crosby suspects it was overshadowed by World War I.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Katherine Anne Porter's 1939 novella *Pale Horse, Pale Rider* is one of the most well-known fictional accounts of the pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The 2006 novel *The Last Town on Earth* focuses on a town which attempts to limit the spread of the flu by preventing people from entering or leaving.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] *The Pull of the Stars* is a 2020 novel by Emma Donoghue set in Dublin during the Spanish flu.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Publishers fast-tracked publication because of the then ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Similarities between a reconstruction of the virus and avian viruses, combined with the human pandemic preceding the first reports of influenza in swine, led researchers to conclude the influenza virus jumped directly from birds to humans, and swine caught the disease from humans.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] More recent research has suggested the strain may have originated in a nonhuman, mammalian species, in 1882–1913.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This ancestor virus diverged about 1913–1915 into the classical swine and human H1N1 influenza lineages.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The last common ancestor of human strains dates between February 1917 and April 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Because pigs are more readily infected with avian influenza viruses than are humans, they were suggested as the original recipients of the virus, passing the virus to humans sometime between 1913 and 1918.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] An effort to recreate the Spanish flu strain (a strain of influenza A subtype H1N1) was a collaboration among the Armed Forces Institute of Pathology, the USDA ARS Southeast Poultry Research Laboratory, and Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York City.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] The effort resulted in the announcement in 2005 that the group had successfully determined the virus' genetic sequence, using historic tissue samples recovered by pathologist Johan Hultin from an Inuit female flu victim buried in the Alaskan permafrost and samples preserved from American soldiers.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This enabled researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the Mount Sinai School of Medicine, led by Dr Terrence Tumpey, to synthesize RNA segments from the H1N1 virus and reconstruct infective virus particles.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These were subsequently used to experimentally infect mice, ferrets, and macaques, providing information about how to prevent and control future pandemics.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 2007, Kobasa et al. reported that monkeys (*Macaca fascicularis*) infected with the recreated flu strain exhibited classic symptoms of the 1918 pandemic, and died from an overreaction of the immune system.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] This may explain why the Spanish flu had its surprising effect on younger, healthier people, as a person with a stronger immune system would potentially have a stronger overreaction.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In December 2008, research by Yoshihiro Kawaoka of the University of Wisconsin linked three specific genes (termed PA, PB1, and PB2) and a nucleoprotein derived from Spanish flu samples to the ability of the 1918 flu virus to invade the lungs and cause pneumonia.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] These genes were inserted into a modern H1N1 strain and triggered similar symptoms in animal testing.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In June 2010, a team at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine reported the 2009 flu pandemic vaccine provided some cross-protection against the Spanish flu pandemic strain.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In 2013, the AIR Worldwide Research and Modeling Group "estimated the effects of a similar pandemic occurring today using the AIR Pandemic Flu Model".
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] In the model, "a modern-day 'Spanish flu' event would result in additional life insurance losses of between US$15.3–27.8 billion in the United States alone", with 188,000–337,000 deaths in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/1918-flu-pandemic-p02] Worobey extracted tissue from the slides to potentially reveal more about the origin of the pathogen.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters was born as the youngest of seven children of parents who were pioneers in Washington state and grew wheat at their homestead.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] He graduated in geology from the University of Washington with a B.Sc. in 1927 and an M.Sc. in 1928.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] He graduated with a Ph.D. in geology in 1930 from Yale University.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] His doctoral dissertation *Geology of the Southern Half of the Chelan [30′] Quadrangle, Washington* was supervised by Adolph Knopf.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] From 1930 to 1951 Waters held an appointment as a faculty member at Stanford University.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] He was leave of absence for the arcademic year 1937–1938 and during WW II from 1942 to 1945.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] For the academic year 1937–1938 he was a Guggenheim Fellow and did research in Scotland and Scandinavia.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] In 1940 he married Elizabeth von Hoene, who was then a student at Mills College.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] During their marriage, she often accompanied him in his fieldwork and served as camp cook.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] After the attack on Pearl Harbor, the United States Geological Survey (USGS) expanded its search for strategic minerals.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters went on an extended leave of absence to serve in the USGS — the main focus of his work was on mercury deposits.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] He first worked in Arkansas and then in several western states.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Before the end of WW II he was sent to search for other metal ores in different parts of the USA.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] In 1945 he returned to his professorial duties at Stanford and began to focus on basalts and other volcanic rocks of the Pacific Northwest.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters, in collaboration with James Gilluly and Alfred Woodford, wrote a textbook *Principles of Geology*, which was published by W.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] The *Principles of Geology* went through 4 editions and for more than two decades remained the leading introductory textbook for geology.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters acquired expertise concerning uranium ores and from 1951 to 1952 participated in the USGS's exploration for uranium ores on the Colorado Plateau.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] In 1952 Waters resigned from Stanford University to accept an appointment at Johns Hopkins University, where he was a professor from 1952 to 1963.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] From 1963 to 1967 he was a professor and chair of the geology department at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] From 1967 to 1972 he was a professor at the University of California, Santa Cruz.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] There he established a Ph.D. program in earth sciences and retired as professor emeritus in 1972.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Santa Cruz, he worked with Richard Virgil Fisher on maar volcanism.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] In retirement as professor emeritus, Waters occasionally taught part-time at the University of Satan Cruz and held visiting professorships at Oregon State University, the University of Texas at El Paso, and California State University, Los Angeles.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] As professor emeritus, he also worked as a research consultant for the USGS and Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters was elected in 1964 a Member of the National Academy of Sciences and in 1966 a Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] In 1982 he was awarded the Penrose Medal of the Geological Society of America.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] In 1983 Aaron and Elizabeth Waters settled in Tacoma, where he continued to write about geology and pursue his hobby of gardening.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Upon his death in 1991, he was survived by his widow, their two daughters, and three grandchildren.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters was a leading expert on the geology of the Pacific Northwest.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] He did research on volcanology, igneous and metamorphic petrology, geomorphology, and tectonics.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Krauskopf, he did important fieldwork on protoplastic deformation found in the Colville batholith.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] Waters was the author or co-author of classic articles on determining the directions of flow in volcanic rocks and on documenting the characteristics of volcanic base surge deposits.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] As a participant in the Apollo program, he contributed to research on lunar geology, including composition and origin of the lunar surface and assessment of Apollo landing sites.
[src:adolph-knopf/aaron-c-waters] He was involved in the geological training of the astronauts, including those astronauts who later made lunar landings.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:adolph-knopf/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The **age of Earth** is estimated to be 4.54 ± 0.05 billion years.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This age corresponds to the final stages of Earth's accretion and planetary differentiation during the early Hadean eon.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Estimates are based on radiometric dating of meteoritic material—the ages of which are approached by those of the oldest-known terrestrial material and lunar samples—and accretion models consistent with observations of planet formation in protoplanetary disks.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Following the development of radiometric dating in the early 20th century, measurements of lead in uranium-rich minerals showed that some were in excess of a billion years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The oldest such minerals analyzed to date, small crystals of zircon from the Jack Hills of Western Australia, are at least 4.404 billion years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Calcium–aluminium-rich inclusions (CAIs), the oldest known solid matter that formed within the Solar System, are 4.5673 ± 0.00016 billion years old, giving a lower limit for the age of the Solar System.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] It is inferred that the accretion of Earth began soon after the formation of CAIs.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Because the duration of this accretion process is not yet adequately constrained—predictions from different models range from around 30 to 100 million years—the difference between the age of Earth and of the oldest rocks is difficult to determine.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] It can also be difficult to determine the exact age of the oldest rocks on Earth, exposed at the surface, as they are aggregates of minerals of possibly different ages.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Studies of strata—the layering of rocks and soil—gave naturalists an appreciation that Earth may have been through many changes during its existence.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] These layers often contained fossilized remains of unknown creatures, leading some to interpret a progression of organisms from layer to layer.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Nicolas Steno in the 17th century was one of the first naturalists to appreciate the connection between fossil remains and strata.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] His observations led him to formulate important stratigraphic concepts (i.e., the "law of superposition" and the "principle of original horizontality").
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In the 1790s, William Smith hypothesized that if two layers of rock at widely differing locations contained similar fossils, then it was very plausible that the layers were the same age.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Smith's nephew and student, John Phillips, later calculated by such means that Earth was about 96 million years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In the mid-18th century, the naturalist Mikhail Lomonosov suggested that Earth had been created separately from, and several hundred thousand years before, the rest of the universe.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Lomonosov's ideas were mostly speculative.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1779 the Comte de Buffon tried to obtain a value for the age of Earth using an experiment: he created a small globe that resembled Earth in composition and then measured its rate of cooling.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This led him to estimate that the Earth was 74,832 years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Other naturalists used these hypotheses to construct a history of Earth, though their timelines were inexact as they did not know how long it took to lay down stratigraphic layers.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1830, geologist Charles Lyell, developing ideas found in James Hutton's works, popularized the concept that the features of Earth were in perpetual change, eroding and reforming continuously, and the rate of this change was roughly constant.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This was a challenge to the traditional view, which saw the history of Earth as dominated by intermittent catastrophes.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Many naturalists were influenced by Lyell to become "uniformitarians" who believed that changes were constant and uniform.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1862, the physicist William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin published calculations that fixed the age of Earth at between 20 million and 400 million years.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] He assumed that Earth had formed as a completely molten object, and determined the amount of time it would take for the near-surface temperature gradient to decrease to its present value.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] His calculations did not account for heat produced via radioactive decay (a then unknown process) or, more significantly, convection inside Earth, which allows the temperature in the upper mantle to remain high much longer, maintaining a high thermal gradient in the crust much longer.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Even more constraining were Thomson's estimates of the age of the Sun, which were based on estimates of its thermal output and a theory that the Sun obtains its energy from gravitational collapse; Thomson estimated that the Sun is about 20 million years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Geologists such as Lyell had difficulty accepting such a short age for Earth.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] For biologists, even 100 million years seemed much too short to be plausible.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, the process of random heritable variation with cumulative selection requires great durations of time, and Darwin stated that Thomson's estimates did not appear to provide enough time.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] According to modern biology, the total evolutionary history from the beginning of life to today has taken place since 3.5 to 3.8 billion years ago, the amount of time which passed since the last universal ancestor of all living organisms as shown by geological dating.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In a lecture in 1869, Darwin's great advocate, Thomas Henry Huxley, attacked Thomson's calculations, suggesting they appeared precise in themselves but were based on faulty assumptions.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Their values were consistent with Thomson's calculations.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] However, they assumed that the Sun was only glowing from the heat of its gravitational contraction.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The process of solar nuclear fusion was not yet known to science.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1892, Thomson was ennobled as Lord Kelvin in appreciation of his many scientific accomplishments.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1895 John Perry challenged Kelvin's figure on the basis of his assumptions on conductivity, and Oliver Heaviside entered the dialogue, considering it "a vehicle to display the ability of his operator method to solve problems of astonishing complexity." Other scientists backed up Kelvin's figures.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Darwin, proposed that Earth and Moon had broken apart in their early days when they were both molten.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] He calculated the amount of time it would have taken for tidal friction to give Earth its current 24-hour day.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] His value of 56 million years was additional evidence that Thomson was on the right track.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The last estimate Kelvin gave, in 1897, was: "that it was more than 20 and less than 40 million year old, and probably much nearer 20 than 40".
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1899 and 1900, John Joly calculated the rate at which the oceans should have accumulated salt from erosion processes and determined that the oceans were about 80 to 100 million years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] By their chemical nature, rock minerals contain certain elements and not others; but in rocks containing radioactive isotopes, the process of radioactive decay generates exotic elements over time.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] By measuring the concentration of the stable end product of the decay, coupled with knowledge of the half life and initial concentration of the decaying element, the age of the rock can be calculated.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Typical radioactive end products are argon from decay of potassium-40, and lead from decay of uranium and thorium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] If the rock becomes molten, as happens in Earth's mantle, such nonradioactive end products typically escape or are redistributed.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Thus the age of the oldest terrestrial rock gives a minimum for the age of Earth, assuming that no rock has been intact for longer than Earth itself.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The discovery of radioactivity introduced another factor in the calculation.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] After Henri Becquerel's initial discovery in 1896, Marie and Pierre Curie discovered the radioactive elements polonium and radium in 1898; and in 1903, Pierre Curie and Albert Laborde announced that radium produces enough heat to melt its own weight in ice in less than an hour.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Geologists quickly realized that this upset the assumptions underlying most calculations of the age of Earth.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] These had assumed that the original heat of Earth and the Sun had dissipated steadily into space, but radioactive decay meant that this heat had been continually replenished.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] George Darwin and John Joly were the first to point this out, in 1903.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Radioactivity, which had overthrown the old calculations, yielded a bonus by providing a basis for new calculations, in the form of radiometric dating.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Ernest Rutherford and Frederick Soddy jointly had continued their work on radioactive materials and concluded that radioactivity was caused by a spontaneous transmutation of atomic elements.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In radioactive decay, an element breaks down into another, lighter element, releasing alpha, beta, or gamma radiation in the process.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] They also determined that a particular isotope of a radioactive element decays into another element at a distinctive rate.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This rate is given in terms of a "half-life", or the amount of time it takes half of a mass of that radioactive material to break down into its "decay product".
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Some radioactive materials have short half-lives; some have long half-lives.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Uranium and thorium have long half-lives and so persist in Earth's crust, but radioactive elements with short half-lives have generally disappeared.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This suggested that it might be possible to measure the age of Earth by determining the relative proportions of radioactive materials in geological samples.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In reality, radioactive elements do not always decay into nonradioactive ("stable") elements directly, instead, decaying into other radioactive elements that have their own half-lives and so on, until they reach a stable element.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] These "decay chains", such as the uranium-radium and thorium series, were known within a few years of the discovery of radioactivity and provided a basis for constructing techniques of radiometric dating.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The pioneers of radioactivity were chemist Bertram B.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Boltwood had conducted studies of radioactive materials as a consultant, and when Rutherford lectured at Yale in 1904, Boltwood was inspired to describe the relationships between elements in various decay series.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Late in 1904, Rutherford took the first step toward radiometric dating by suggesting that the alpha particles released by radioactive decay could be trapped in a rocky material as helium atoms.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] At the time, Rutherford was only guessing at the relationship between alpha particles and helium atoms, but he would prove the connection four years later.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Soddy and Sir William Ramsay had just determined the rate at which radium produces alpha particles, and Rutherford proposed that he could determine the age of a rock sample by measuring its concentration of helium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] He dated a rock in his possession to an age of 40 million years by this technique.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Rutherford assumed that the rate of decay of radium as determined by Ramsay and Soddy was accurate and that helium did not escape from the sample over time.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Rutherford's scheme was inaccurate, but it was a useful first step.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Boltwood focused on the end products of decay series.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In 1905, he suggested that lead was the final stable product of the decay of radium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] It was already known that radium was an intermediate product of the decay of uranium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Rutherford joined in, outlining a decay process in which radium emitted five alpha particles through various intermediate products to end up with lead, and speculated that the radium–lead decay chain could be used to date rock samples.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Boltwood did the legwork and by the end of 1905 had provided dates for 26 separate rock samples, ranging from 92 to 570 million years.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] He did not publish these results, which was fortunate because they were flawed by measurement errors and poor estimates of the half-life of radium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Boltwood refined his work and finally published the results in 1907.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Boltwood's paper pointed out that samples taken from comparable layers of strata had similar lead-to-uranium ratios, and that samples from older layers had a higher proportion of lead, except where there was evidence that lead had leached out of the sample.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] His studies were flawed by the fact that the decay series of thorium was not understood, which led to incorrect results for samples that contained both uranium and thorium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] However, his calculations were far more accurate than any that had been performed to that time.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Refinements in the technique would later give ages for Boltwood's 26 samples of 410 million to 2.2 billion years.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Although Boltwood published his paper in a prominent geological journal, the geological community had little interest in radioactivity.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Boltwood gave up work on radiometric dating and went on to investigate other decay series.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Rutherford remained mildly curious about the issue of the age of Earth but did little work on it.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Robert Strutt tinkered with Rutherford's helium method until 1910 and then ceased.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] However, Strutt's student Arthur Holmes became interested in radiometric dating and continued to work on it after everyone else had given up.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Holmes focused on lead dating because he regarded the helium method as unpromising.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] He performed measurements on rock samples and concluded in 1911 that the oldest (a sample from Ceylon) was about 1.6 billion years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] These calculations were not particularly trustworthy.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] For example, he assumed that the samples had contained only uranium and no lead when they were formed.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] More important research was published in 1913.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] It showed that elements generally exist in multiple variants with different masses, or "isotopes".
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In the 1930s, isotopes would be shown to have nuclei with differing numbers of the neutral particles known as "neutrons".
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] In that same year, other research was published establishing the rules for radioactive decay, allowing more precise identification of decay series.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Many geologists felt these new discoveries made radiometric dating so complicated as to be worthless.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Holmes felt that they gave him tools to improve his techniques, and he plodded ahead with his research, publishing before and after the First World War.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] His work was generally ignored until the 1920s, though in 1917 Joseph Barrell, a professor of geology at Yale, redrew geological history as it was understood at the time to conform to Holmes's findings in radiometric dating.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Barrell's research determined that the layers of strata had not all been laid down at the same rate, and so current rates of geological change could not be used to provide accurate timelines of the history of Earth.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Holmes' persistence finally began to pay off in 1921, when the speakers at the yearly meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science came to a rough consensus that Earth was a few billion years old and that radiometric dating was credible.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Holmes published *The Age of the Earth, an Introduction to Geological Ideas* in 1927 in which he presented a range of 1.6 to 3.0 billion years.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] No great push to embrace radiometric dating followed, however, and the die-hards in the geological community stubbornly resisted.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] They had never cared for attempts by physicists to intrude in their domain, and had successfully ignored them so far.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The growing weight of evidence finally tilted the balance in 1931, when the National Research Council of the US National Academy of Sciences decided to resolve the question of the age of Earth by appointing a committee to investigate.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Holmes, being one of the few people who was trained in radiometric dating techniques, was a committee member and in fact wrote most of the final report.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Thus, Holmes' report concluded that radioactive dating was the only reliable means of pinning down a geologic time scale.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Questions of bias were deflected by the great and exacting detail of the report.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] It described the methods used, the care with which measurements were made, and their error bars and limitations.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Radiometric dating continues to be the predominant way scientists date geologic time scales.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Techniques for radioactive dating have been tested and fine-tuned on an ongoing basis since the 1960s.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Forty or so different dating techniques have been utilized to date, working on a wide variety of materials.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Dates for the same sample using these different techniques are in very close agreement on the age of the material.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Possible contamination problems do exist, but they have been studied and dealt with by careful investigation, leading to sample preparation procedures being minimized to limit the chance of contamination.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] An age of 4.55 ± 0.07 billion years, very close to today's accepted age, was determined by Clair Cameron Patterson using uranium–lead isotope dating (specifically lead–lead dating) on several meteorites including the Canyon Diablo meteorite and published in 1956.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The quoted age of Earth is derived, in part, from the Canyon Diablo meteorite for several important reasons and is built upon a modern understanding of cosmochemistry built up over decades of research.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] To mitigate this effect it is usual to date several minerals in the same sample, to provide an isochron.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Alternatively, more than one dating system may be used on a sample to check the date.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Some meteorites are furthermore considered to represent the primitive material from which the accreting solar disk was formed.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Some have behaved as closed systems (for some isotopic systems) soon after the solar disk and the planets formed.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] To date, these assumptions are supported by much scientific observation and repeated isotopic dates, and it is certainly a more robust hypothesis than that which assumes a terrestrial rock has retained its original composition.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Nevertheless, ancient Archaean lead ores of galena have been used to date the formation of Earth as these represent the earliest formed lead-only minerals on the planet and record the earliest homogeneous lead–lead isotope systems on the planet.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] These have returned age dates of 4.54 billion years with a precision of as little as 1% margin for error.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The Canyon Diablo meteorite was used because it is both large and representative of a particularly rare type of meteorite that contains sulfide minerals (particularly troilite, FeS), metallic nickel-iron alloys, plus silicate minerals.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This is important because the presence of the three mineral phases allows investigation of isotopic dates using samples that provide a great separation in concentrations between parent and daughter nuclides.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This is particularly true of uranium and lead.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Lead is strongly chalcophilic and is found in the sulfide at a much greater concentration than in the silicate, versus uranium.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Because of this segregation in the parent and daughter nuclides during the formation of the meteorite, this allowed a much more precise date of the formation of the solar disk and hence the planets than ever before.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The age determined from the Canyon Diablo meteorite has been confirmed by hundreds of other age determinations, from both terrestrial samples and other meteorites.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The meteorite samples, however, show a spread from 4.53 to 4.58 billion years ago.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This is interpreted as the duration of formation of the solar nebula and its collapse into the solar disk to form the Sun and the planets.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] This 50-million-year time span allows for accretion of the planets from the original solar dust and meteorites.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The Moon, as another extraterrestrial body that has not undergone plate tectonics and that has no atmosphere, provides quite precise age dates from the samples returned from the Apollo missions.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Rocks returned from the Moon have been dated at a maximum of 4.51 billion years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Martian meteorites that have landed upon Earth have also been dated to around 4.5 billion years old by lead–lead dating.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Lunar samples, since they have not been disturbed by weathering, plate tectonics or material moved by organisms, can also provide dating by direct electron microscope examination of cosmic ray tracks.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] The accumulation of dislocations generated by high energy cosmic ray particle impacts provides another confirmation of the isotopic dates.
[src:adolph-knopf/age-of-the-earth] Cosmic ray dating is only useful on material that has not been melted, since melting erases the crystalline structure of the material, and wipes away the tracks left by the particles.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:adolph-knopf/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:adolph-knopf/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:adolph-knopf/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:adolph-knopf/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:adolph-knopf/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:adolph-knopf/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
